answers.body_markdown:
You can achieve such effect with abstraction for the data you need to validate. You need an interface with methods to get the data you need. Let&#39;s say:
```
public interface DatesData {

  LocalDateTime startDate();

  LocalDateTime endDate();
}
```
Not a really good name, but ok for example purposes. Then enable your actual validator to validate instances of this interface, not `Object` as it is now. Like this you can also simplify it a lot:
```
public class NonOverlappingDatesValidator implements ConstraintValidator&lt;NonOverlappingDates, DatesData&gt; {

  @Override
  public boolean isValid(DatesData data, ConstraintValidatorContext context) {
    return data.startDate().isBefore(data.endDate());
  }
}
```
`NonOverlappingDatesValidator` can now validate **any** class implementing `DatesData`. `IdentityCardDTO` becomes:
```
@Data
@NonOverlappingDates
public class IdentityCardDTO implements DatesData {

  //the rest of the fields, getters, setters, etc.

  @Override
  public LocalDateTime startDate() {
    return startDate;
  }

  @Override
  public LocalDateTime endDate() {
    return endDate;
  }
}
```
This simplifies `NonOverlappingDates` as well, since you no longer need `start()` and `end()` methods.

